version: 1
display_name: PHTN-50-000228 - The Photon operating system must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses.
global_description: |-
  The presence of "martian" packets (which have impossible addresses) as well as spoofed packets, source-routed packets, and redirects could be a sign of nefarious network activity. Logging these packets enables this activity to be detected.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - PHTN-50-000228
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_photon_5:
    type: custom
    desc: The Photon operating system must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses.
    control_id: PHTN-50-000228
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      At the command line, run the following command to verify martian packets are logged:

      # /sbin/sysctl -a --pattern "net.ipv4.conf.(all|default).log_martians"

      Expected result:

      net.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians = 1
      net.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians = 1

      If the "log_martians" kernel parameters are not set to "1", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      The presence of "martian" packets (which have impossible addresses) as well as spoofed packets, source-routed packets, and redirects could be a sign of nefarious network activity. Logging these packets enables this activity to be detected.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      /etc/sysctl.d/zz-stig-hardening.conf

      Add or update the following lines:

      net.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians = 1
      net.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians = 1

      At the command line, run the following command to load the new configuration:

      # /sbin/sysctl --load /etc/sysctl.d/zz-stig-hardening.conf

      Note: If the file zz-stig-hardening.conf does not exist it must be created.
